SIMPLE: senna
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Senna
<hw>Sen"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. It. & Sp.
<ets>sena</ets>, Pg. <ets>sene</ets>, F. <ets>s⟦eacute⟧n⟦eacute⟧</ets>;
all fr. Ar. <ets>san⟦amac⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld>
<def>The leaves of several leguminous plants of the genus
<gen>Cassia</gen>. (<spn>Cassia acutifolia</spn>, <spn>Cassia
angustifolia</spn>, etc.). They constitute a valuable but nauseous
cathartic medicine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The plants themselves, native to
the East, but now cultivated largely in the south of Europe and in the
West Indies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bladder senna</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Bladder</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Wild senna</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the <spn>Cassia Marilandica</spn>, growing in the
United States, the leaves of which are used medicinally, like those of
the officinal senna.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1310 --></p>

<p><ent>Sennachy</ent>⟦br⟧
